tbl <- data.frame(nums = c(1, -1, 2, 3), strs = c("a", "b", "b", "c"))
tbl$nums < 0
## [1] FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE
sum(tbl$nums < 0)
## [1] 1
sum(tbl$strs == "b")
## [1] 2

sw_humans <- filter(starwars, species == "Human")

  • Question 3.b: Here is a helper function that can get the characters that match a particular mass value in the starwars table:
sw_mass_max <- function(m) {
  filter(starwars, mass == m) |> pull(name)
}

sw_mass_max(77)
## [1] "Luke Skywalker" "Obi-Wan Kenobi" "Wedge Antilles"

Vectorized Computations

Question 2b and 2c use vectorized computations. I wanted to provide a few additional details. We originally saw vectorized computations when using relational operators:

vals <- c(1, -1, 0, 4)
vals <= 0
## [1] FALSE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE

Many other operations in R are also vectorized in that they operate on each item in a vector. Some examples:

vals + 1
## [1] 2 0 1 5
2 * vals
## [1]  2 -2  0  8
vals^2 # vals squared
## [1]  1  1  0 16

If you have two vectors, you can perform vectorized operations on them together:

more_vals <- c(10, 20, 30, 40)
vals + more_vals
## [1] 11 19 30 44
more_vals * vals
## [1]  10 -20   0 160

Be careful, when using vectors of different length, R will try to make that happen for you:

c(1, 2) + c(3, 4, 5)
## Warning in c(1, 2) + c(3, 4, 5): longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
## [1] 4 6 6

R will try to recycle the shorter as needed. Notice that we got:

c(1 + 4, 2 + 6, 1 + 5)
## [1] 5 8 6

Sometimes this behavior is what we want, but usually this warning is a sign something bad is happening.

Joint Distributions and Conditional Distributions

Question 3.c asks talks about conditional distributions. As a brief reminder of types of distributions:

  • Marginal distribution: a distribution of a single variable (i.e., the set of all possible values and counts)
  • Joint distribution: a distribution of two or more variables (i.e., all possible combinations of values and counts)
  • Conditional distribution: the distribution that is formed for a subset of the joint distribution (i.e., looking within a specific subset of the data, what are all possible values of an other variable and its counts)

Some examples.

Marginal Distributions

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = class)) + geom_bar()

Joint Distributions

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) + geom_jitter()

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) + geom_bin_2d()
